  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide framework for global anti-money laundering standards\n\n2. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Establishing common reporting standards\n- Requiring financial institutions to implement Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Mandating suspicious transaction reporting\n- Creating cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n3. Legal Harmonization\n- Encouraging countries to adopt consistent legal definitions\n- Standardizing criminal penalties\n- Creating mutual legal assistance frameworks\n- Promoting international cooperation in investigations\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Extradition agreements\n- International law enforcement collaboration\n- Asset seizure and recovery protocols\n\n5. Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- Facilitating international information exchange\n- Coordinating cross-border investigations\n- Supporting global anti-money laundering efforts\n\n6. Sanctions and Multilateral Pressure\n- Economic sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- International reputation mechanisms\n- Financial system exclusion for persistently non-cooperative countries\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered approach to combating money laundering globally.",
